  <p>
    <em>Mesons.</em> Mesons are those particles that participate in the strong interaction and have integer spin.
    That is, those hadrons that are also bosons are called mesons.
    Their masses range from <m>0.135\Xunits{GeV/ c^2 }</m> up to <m>11\Xunits{GeV/ c^2 }</m> or more,
    and more are still being discovered.
    Only a few have lifetimes longer than about <m>10^{-20}\Xunits{s}</m>.
    Unlike leptons or baryons the number of mesons is not conserved <mdash/> mesons can be created or destroyed in reactions.
    Pions and kaons are two examples of meson types.
    <xref ref="table_mesons">Table</xref> lists several others.
  </p>
